      "link": null,
      "locked": false
    },
    {
      "id": "DYHVZBjnakbbihvFtS5kr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 288.422119140625,
      "y": -293.9042410714285,
      "width": 248.62451171875,
      "height": 302.40000000000003,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aL",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 711238091,
      "version": 559,
      "versionNonce": 1161159525,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1782919595801,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "In create_session, you used\ntimezone.utc, but then in\nget_current_user, you used\ndatetime.utcnow(). The problem is\nthat the first one has a timezone\nattached when it's recorded, while\nthe second function compares the\nexpiration time against a time that\nhas no timezone information. This\ncan cause issues for you.\nTry to use\ndatetime.now(timezone.utc)\neverywhere consistently.\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "-L6lOlVG0YGGHk6z1Fj4m",
      "originalText": "In create_session, you used timezone.utc, but then in get_current_user, you used datetime.utcnow(). The problem is that the first one has a timezone attached when it's recorded, while the second function compares the expiration time against a time that has no timezone information. This can cause issues for you.\nTry to use datetime.now(timezone.utc) everywhere consistently.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
